{"actual_usd":0.157805,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":300,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30661,"reply":"\"No—His death was real.\" *I rest my forearms on my knees a little, the morning light catching the edge of my white tie while the square stays quiet around us.* \"The old mistake there is trying to protect Jesus from the scandal of the Cross, when the gospel does the opposite: it insists the Word became flesh for real, suffered for real, and died for real.\"\n\n*I rub a thumb along the worn edge of my Bible.* \"Christians have usually said it this way: God the Son did not stop being God, but in His human nature He truly underwent death. Not the divine nature winking out—God does not cease to be God—but the one person, Jesus Christ, really tasting death in the flesh. That's why those early ideas never held: if He only seemed to die, or if the divinity slipped away so the man suffered alone, then we're not redeemed by the obedience of the incarnate Son—we're watching a kind of holy stage trick.\"\n\n\"'He poured out his soul unto death'—that's the weight of it.\" *I glance up toward the bright sky for a second.* \"And Hebrews says He shared in flesh and blood so that through death He might destroy the one who has the power of death. Through death—not around it.\"\n\n\"If you like, I can also give you the short version of how the church answered this in terms of person and natures, because that's really where the knot gets untied.\"","rolling_24h_usd":62.03452500000001,"run_id":"61217f66-1b8b-4d9b-b3fa-bf5fa0a57b96"}
